Create a data set, htvswt (height vs weight) for the analyses that drops any rows with ‘NA’ for height or weight.

htvswt<-IntData %>%
  filter(height>= 25) %>%
  drop_na(total_weight_wet) %>%
  drop_na(height)

Make a quick scatterplot to visualize the data. We will call this scatterplot plothtvswt so we can call it later and overlay model results on it.

plothtvswt<-
  ggplot(htvswt,aes(x=height,y=total_weight_wet,colour=region))+
  geom_point(aes(x=height,y=total_weight_wet))+
  theme_cowplot(12)
plothtvswt

Now make a simple model. This model does not have interactions, so the slopes for all regions will be the same. This will probably not be a good fit, but I’m trying to illustrate how adding interactions allows the other slopes to vary from the reference.

model1 <- glm(total_weight_wet ~ height + region,data=htvswt)
summary(model1)

R has arbitrarily specified AH as our reference (you can manually change this if needed), so the slope of weight vs height for AH is represented by the row ‘height.’ The estimate (1.20154) is significantly different from 0 (p <2e-16). In simple words, this means each 1 unit increase in height, results in about a 1.2 unit increase in weight.

Since we did not include interaction terms, the other slopes are restricted to being the same as the reference (again, this is not ideal, but we are going to build on this model). The estimates for the non-reference groups represent how the intercepts differ from the reference. For example, height being equal, the average weight of an oyster in CR will be 7.27 units less than those at AH.

This model is probably flawed for a few reasons. First, we have reason to suspect that the slopes should not be the same. Second, we probably need a different distribution. Third, we need to deal with temporal autocorrelation. We can keep adding terms to correct these. First, lets graph this model so we can visually see why it is not a good fit.

#get model predictions
resultsmodel1<-predict.glm(model1,se.fit= TRUE)
#Update resultsmodel1 to include oritginal model data and predictions.
resultsmodel1<-cbind(htvswt,resultsmodel1)

Now that we have predictions, we can overlay them on the plot we made earlier.

plotmodel1 <-
  #call the plot we already made
  plothtvswt+
  #add a line for the model predictions.
  geom_line(data=resultsmodel1,aes(y=fit),size=1)+
  theme_cowplot(12)
plotmodel1

Gross. That fit is not good. We don’t need to run any residual tests. It is very obviously a bad fit. One thing that would improve the fit is allowing the slopes to be different. Interactions can accomplish this.

So, we’ll create a second model and allow for interactions. Note that in the glm formula the asterisk (*) signifies interactions. If you just include the asterisk, R will automatically include the interactions for every possible combination of main effects, but you could specify these manually.

For example, the formulas below are equivalent: model2 <- glm(total_weight_wet ~ height * region,data=htvswt) model2 <- glm(total_weight_wet ~ height + region + height * region,data=htvswt)

You could even specify them by each value in the term (e.g. AH, CR, EC, IL), but I digress. Let’s get back to the model. We will create it just like before, but I’ll add the interaction term.

model2 <- glm(total_weight_wet ~ height * region,data=htvswt)
summary(model2)

The interaction term changes the interpretation a bit. The height row still represents AH. The other region rows (e.g. regionCR) still represent how the mean of these groups differs from AH, but since the slopes are zero, this number only applies when x = 0. (You could, of course, calcaulte out differences at any value of x, though.)

The interaction rows tell you how the slopes of each area region differ from that of the reference group.

Let’s graph it using the same process as before.

You can see, it’s a better fit, but still not great.

We might need a log transformation.Let’s make some plots to visually see if transformation will help.

First, we’ll try taking the log of Y

plotTransy<-
  ggplot(htvswt,aes(x=(height),y=log(total_weight_wet),colour=region))+
  geom_point(aes(x=(height),y=log(total_weight_wet)))+
  labs(x='Height',y='Log(Weight)')+
  ggtitle("Transform Y, Weight")+
  theme_cowplot(12)
plotTransy

It’s better, but there is still some curve to it. Let’s try also taking the log of y.

plotTransXY<-
  ggplot(htvswt,aes(x=log(height),y=log(total_weight_wet),colour=region))+
  geom_point(aes(x=log(height),y=log(total_weight_wet)))+
  labs(x='Log(Height (mm))',y='Log(Weight (g))')+
  ggtitle("Transform X and Y, Height and Weight")+
  theme_cowplot(12)
plotTransXY

That looks much more linear! We will model these data.

model3 <- glm(log(total_weight_wet) ~ log(height) * region,data=htvswt)

plotmodel3 <-

Here is a quick refresher on back transforming log models. https://cscu.cornell.edu/wp-content/uploads/83_logv.pdf

plotmodel3trans <-
  plothtvswt+
  geom_line(data=resultsmodel3,aes(y=exp(fit)),size=1)+
  labs(x='Height (mm)',y='Weight (g)')+
  theme_cowplot(12)
plotmodel3trans
